Kubernetes Cluster Deployment
Prerequisites
Basic Linux command-line knowledge
Understanding of containerization concepts (Docker basics)
Familiarity with YAML syntax
Basic networking concepts (ports, IP addresses)
Root or sudo access to a Linux machine
Learning Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Set up a single-node Kubernetes cluster using Minikube
Deploy containerized applications as pods
Create and manage Kubernetes services
Expose applications for external access
Verify cluster health and application status
Environment Setup
System Requirements
Linux machine (Ubuntu 20.04+ or similar)
Minimum 2 CPU cores
2GB RAM minimum (4GB recommended)
20GB free disk space
Internet connection for downloading tools
Install Required Tools
Step 1: Install Docker

# Update package index
sudo apt-get update

# Install Docker
sudo apt-get install -y docker.io

# Start and enable Docker
sudo systemctl start docker
sudo systemctl enable docker

# Add current user to docker group
sudo usermod -aG docker $USER

# Apply group changes (or logout/login)
newgrp docker
Step 2: Install kubectl

# Download kubectl binary
curl -LO "https://dl.k8s.io/release/$(curl -L -s https://dl.k8s.io/release/stable.txt)/bin/linux/amd64/kubectl"

# Make it executable
chmod +x kubectl

# Move to system path
sudo mv kubectl /usr/local/bin/

# Verify installation
kubectl version --client
Step 3: Install Minikube

# Download Minikube
curl -LO https://storage.googleapis.com/minikube/releases/latest/minikube-linux-amd64

# Install Minikube
sudo install minikube-linux-amd64 /usr/local/bin/minikube

# Verify installation
minikube version
Task 1: Setup Kubernetes Cluster
Step 1: Start Minikube Cluster
# Start Minikube with Docker driver
minikube start --driver=docker

# Wait for cluster to be ready (this may take 2-3 minutes)
Step 2: Verify Cluster Status
# Check cluster status
minikube status

# View cluster information
kubectl cluster-info

# List all nodes
kubectl get nodes

# Check system pods
kubectl get pods -n kube-system
Expected output should show:

Minikube running
One node in "Ready" state
System pods in "Running" state
Step 3: Enable Minikube Dashboard (Optional)
# Enable metrics server
minikube addons enable metrics-server

# View enabled addons
minikube addons list
Task 2: Deploy Pods and Services
Step 1: Create Application Deployment
Create a deployment manifest file:

# Create working directory
mkdir -p ~/k8s-lab
cd ~/k8s-lab

# Create deployment file
cat > nginx-deployment.yaml << 'EOF'
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: nginx-deployment
  labels:
    app: nginx
spec:
  replicas: 3
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: nginx
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: nginx
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: nginx
        image: nginx:1.21
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80
        resources:
          requests:
            memory: "64Mi"
            cpu: "100m"
          limits:
            memory: "128Mi"
            cpu: "200m"
EOF
Apply the deployment:

# Deploy the application
kubectl apply -f nginx-deployment.yaml

# Watch deployment progress
kubectl get deployments -w
# Press Ctrl+C after deployment shows 3/3 ready
Step 2: Verify Pod Deployment
# List all pods
kubectl get pods

# Get detailed pod information
kubectl get pods -o wide

# Describe a specific pod (replace POD_NAME with actual pod name)
kubectl describe pod <POD_NAME>

# Check pod logs
kubectl logs <POD_NAME>
Step 3: Create Service to Expose Application
Create a service manifest:

cat > nginx-service.yaml << 'EOF'
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: nginx-service
spec:
  type: NodePort
  selector:
    app: nginx
  ports:
  - protocol: TCP
    port: 80
    targetPort: 80
    nodePort: 30080
EOF
Apply the service:

# Create the service
kubectl apply -f nginx-service.yaml

# Verify service creation
kubectl get services

# Get detailed service information
kubectl describe service nginx-service
Step 4: Access the Application
# Get Minikube IP
minikube ip

# Get service URL
minikube service nginx-service --url

# Test the application
curl $(minikube service nginx-service --url)
You should see the default Nginx welcome page HTML.

Step 5: Scale the Deployment
# Scale deployment to 5 replicas
kubectl scale deployment nginx-deployment --replicas=5

# Watch scaling progress
kubectl get pods -w
# Press Ctrl+C after all pods are running

# Verify replica count
kubectl get deployment nginx-deployment
Step 6: Create a Custom Application Deployment
Create a simple web application deployment:

cat > webapp-deployment.yaml << 'EOF'
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: webapp
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: webapp
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: webapp
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: webapp
        image: hashicorp/http-echo
        args:
        - "-text=Hello from Kubernetes Pod"
        - "-listen=:8080"
        ports:
        - containerPort: 8080
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: webapp-service
spec:
  type: NodePort
  selector:
    app: webapp
  ports:
  - protocol: TCP
    port: 8080
    targetPort: 8080
    nodePort: 30081
EOF
Deploy and test:

# Apply the configuration
kubectl apply -f webapp-deployment.yaml

# Wait for pods to be ready
kubectl wait --for=condition=ready pod -l app=webapp --timeout=60s

# Test the application
curl $(minikube service webapp-service --url)
Verification
Verify Cluster Health
# Check all resources in default namespace
kubectl get all

# Verify node status
kubectl get nodes

# Check cluster component status
kubectl get componentstatuses
Verify Deployments
# List all deployments
kubectl get deployments

# Expected output:
# - nginx-deployment: 5/5 replicas ready
# - webapp: 2/2 replicas ready
Verify Services
# List all services
kubectl get services

# Test nginx service
curl $(minikube service nginx-service --url)

# Test webapp service
curl $(minikube service webapp-service --url)
Verify Pods
# Count running pods
kubectl get pods --field-selector=status.phase=Running | wc -l

# Should show 7 running pods (5 nginx + 2 webapp)

# Check pod resource usage
kubectl top pods
View Logs
# View logs from nginx deployment
kubectl logs -l app=nginx --tail=20

# View logs from webapp deployment
kubectl logs -l app=webapp --tail=20
Troubleshooting Tips
Pods not starting:

# Check pod events
kubectl describe pod <POD_NAME>

# Check pod logs
kubectl logs <POD_NAME>

# Check if images are pulling
kubectl get pods -o wide
Service not accessible:

# Verify service endpoints
kubectl get endpoints

# Check service configuration
kubectl describe service <SERVICE_NAME>

# Ensure Minikube tunnel is not needed
minikube service list
Minikube issues:

# Stop and restart Minikube
minikube stop
minikube start

# Delete and recreate cluster
minikube delete
minikube start --driver=docker
Resource constraints:

# Check node resources
kubectl describe node minikube

# View resource usage
kubectl top nodes
kubectl top pods
Cleanup (Optional)
# Delete deployments
kubectl delete deployment nginx-deployment webapp

# Delete services
kubectl delete service nginx-service webapp-service

# Stop Minikube
minikube stop

# Delete Minikube cluster (complete cleanup)
minikube delete
Conclusion
In this lab, you successfully:

Installed and configured Minikube for local Kubernetes development
Created a single-node Kubernetes cluster
Deployed multiple containerized applications using Deployments
Exposed applications using Services with NodePort type
Scaled deployments dynamically
Verified cluster health and application accessibility
Key Concepts Learned:

Minikube: Local Kubernetes cluster for development and testing
Deployments: Declarative way to manage pod replicas
Services: Stable network endpoints for accessing pods
kubectl: Command-line tool for Kubernetes cluster management
Scaling: Adjusting application capacity based on demand
Real-World Applications:

Development and testing environments before production deployment
Microservices architecture implementation
Container orchestration and management
High availability and load balancing
Rolling updates and rollbacks
This foundation prepares you for more advanced Kubernetes concepts like ConfigMaps, Secrets, Persistent Volumes, and multi-node cluster management.
